1
00:00:01,870 --> 00:00:26,240
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambudasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambudasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambudasa

2
00:00:27,772 --> 00:00:31,759
Homage to the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:37,427 --> 00:00:47,924
So, what I want to give you some ideas about or discuss, and I wouldn't say this is completely worked out,

4
00:00:48,496 --> 00:01:01,189
is these two attitudes that we have in society when something goes wrong we have a pacifist approach and the just war and

5
00:01:03,143 --> 00:01:08,310
we have, at least in Western religions, very strong arguments for just war.

6
00:01:09,350 --> 00:01:20,484
I think Thomas Aquinas, the medieval philosopher, who had a great effect on the West, talks about the just war, you see, and gives all sorts of conditions for what makes it just.

7
00:01:21,426 --> 00:01:23,588
One of them is defensive rather than offensive.

8
00:01:24,409 --> 00:01:26,331
Things like that.

9
00:01:26,352 --> 00:01:30,938
Now, from a Buddhist point of view, remember that we always start with ourselves.

10
00:01:31,197 --> 00:01:32,560
We always start here.

11
00:01:33,096 --> 00:01:43,706
And it's recognising how we treat ourselves that we can then project that onto a given situation, political or otherwise.

12
00:01:45,487 --> 00:01:47,028
Now, let's think on, you see.

13
00:01:47,429 --> 00:01:57,778
Supposing now I'm sitting and feelings of anger, feelings of revenge arise.

14
00:01:58,218 --> 00:01:58,739
What do I do?

15
00:01:58,759 --> 00:02:01,921
I suffer them, don't I?

16
00:02:02,745 --> 00:02:09,316
I accept them as unwholesome and I sit there and I suffer them.

17
00:02:09,336 --> 00:02:14,063
Feelings and attitudes of greed, of getting, power, riches, fame.

18
00:02:15,246 --> 00:02:15,826
So what do I do?

19
00:02:15,847 --> 00:02:18,792
I just sit there and suffer them.

20
00:02:19,492 --> 00:02:21,716
Allow them to come up and die away.

21
00:02:22,997 --> 00:02:26,743
So we can see that in our meditation we have a pacifist approach.

22
00:02:27,485 --> 00:02:28,467
On the other hand,

23
00:02:30,639 --> 00:02:39,572
When I'm lazy, when the body says lie down, when the mind says have a kip, see, I do something, I get up, I move.

24
00:02:41,735 --> 00:02:45,139
I follow a certain discipline, I have to get up and follow the schedule.

25
00:02:47,783 --> 00:02:52,590
I determine very strongly to put the mind on the present moment.

26
00:02:54,192 --> 00:02:59,819
This is all force, this is all determination, a force for the good.

27
00:03:01,538 --> 00:03:30,972
so we have a dual approach even in our spiritual life sometimes we have to suffer it and sometimes we have to put energy into our practice depending on the situation now if that energy we put into the practice is laced with some sort of achieving some sort of aggression then that force turns into violence

28
00:03:31,575 --> 00:03:59,018
becomes a violent force so here I think we have three definitions pacifism is the approach to something whereby we allow that energy to die away force is the energy necessary to put right what is wrong and violence is the same energy laced with anger aggression

29
00:04:04,668 --> 00:04:08,391
So that's how we behave inwardly as meditators.

30
00:04:09,092 --> 00:04:13,236
We know that when we're pushing something away which we don't like, that's an aggression.

31
00:04:14,399 --> 00:04:16,420
We have to bear with it, we have to suffer with it.

32
00:04:19,584 --> 00:04:26,973
And what we realise is that in this pacifist approach to ourselves, inside ourselves, we have to bear with it.

33
00:04:27,033 --> 00:04:31,958
So there's a sacrificial element to it.

34
00:04:33,946 --> 00:04:37,930
There's a sense of being the happy victim.

35
00:04:39,151 --> 00:04:43,836
Now it's easy for us to do that inside because we recognize that we've created all this stuff.

36
00:04:45,557 --> 00:04:48,500
So we have to have a certain patience towards it.

37
00:04:48,560 --> 00:04:50,583
And patience means a willingness to suffer.

38
00:04:52,665 --> 00:04:53,105
Kanti.

39
00:04:53,425 --> 00:04:54,226
It's a willingness to suffer.

40
00:04:54,427 --> 00:04:57,209
And the Buddha actually calls it the highest form of ascetic practice.

41
00:04:58,531 --> 00:05:00,213
The highest form of ascetic practice.

42
00:05:01,654 --> 00:05:02,855
So it's a suffering practice.

43
00:05:03,511 --> 00:05:28,742
which we go through a bearing which we go through in order to get rid of suffering so if we now extend that psychology outwards and we look at the scriptures there are one or two incidences where the Buddha is confronted with violence

44
00:05:30,646 --> 00:05:42,480
The first one relates to an incident which happened in his Sakya clan where the local king, which has a sort of difficult name, Viduddaba, asked for a bride.

45
00:05:43,721 --> 00:05:49,449
And the Sakyans, being of a high caste, decided that the king was definitely not worthy of one of them.

46
00:05:49,490 --> 00:05:51,632
So they shipped him a slave girl.

47
00:05:53,233 --> 00:05:56,057
And the marriage went ahead and everything was lovely and beautiful.

48
00:05:56,939 --> 00:06:00,163
And then one day Viduddaba decided to visit his in-laws.

49
00:06:00,733 --> 00:06:01,896
And turned up, you see.

50
00:06:02,656 --> 00:06:03,819
And so the story goes.

51
00:06:04,661 --> 00:06:12,435
Somebody heard somebody slag off his queen, one of the Saccans, as an ordinary slave girl, you see.

52
00:06:13,055 --> 00:06:19,687
And one of his retinue heard this, told it to the king, and the king, of course, was livid.

53
00:06:21,254 --> 00:06:31,730
So getting back home, he couldn't contain his anger and he decided that the only way to re-establish his dignity was to wipe out the Sakins.

54
00:06:33,211 --> 00:06:36,237
So he gathered his army with the elephants and horses and off he went.

55
00:06:36,838 --> 00:06:42,225
The news came to the Buddha and he went off and he stood in front of the army, in front of the king.

56
00:06:43,588 --> 00:06:47,733
What he said we don't know, but it was a good enough argument for the king to turn back.

57
00:06:49,334 --> 00:06:55,040
However, the king must have stewed on it a bit and decided that, no, he was perfectly right, he was going to slaughter the Sakins.

58
00:06:55,540 --> 00:06:59,605
So off he got on his horse again, or his elephant, and made his way.

59
00:06:59,764 --> 00:07:01,047
Again, the Buddha appeared.

60
00:07:02,608 --> 00:07:07,353
The argument must have again won the day and the king turned back.

61
00:07:07,374 --> 00:07:09,036
He got back there and it stewed even more.

62
00:07:09,235 --> 00:07:13,279
So this time he got on his elephant again and he thought, well, you know.

63
00:07:13,300 --> 00:07:16,764
Now when this came to the Buddha's attention, he said he couldn't do anything.

64
00:07:17,704 --> 00:07:19,307
He said the karma was too strong.

65
00:07:19,759 --> 00:07:40,029
so Viduddha ended up killing a lot of his people there's the only incident of what you might call force in the scripture that I've come across

66
00:07:42,202 --> 00:07:48,353
is an occasion when they're reading, the monks are all together reading the Patimokkha.

67
00:07:48,894 --> 00:07:51,278
So this is something that monks go through every two weeks.

68
00:07:53,041 --> 00:07:56,468
It's actually, yes, every two weeks, the full and the new moon.

69
00:07:57,550 --> 00:07:58,831
And all monks are supposed to gather.

70
00:07:59,372 --> 00:08:01,916
They're supposed to confess to each other any transgression.

71
00:08:02,759 --> 00:08:04,802
And then they enter into the meeting.

72
00:08:05,086 --> 00:08:32,798
the meeting opens and basically the rules are read that's all the rules are read so it's an act of confession purification and a reminder of what the holy life's about then usually there's a talk sometimes a bit of chanting and that's about it so that happens every two weeks so the Buddha's sitting there and he's got lots of monks in front of him and he's got his major disciples by him we know that Moggallana was there Moggallana was the second chief disciple

73
00:08:33,553 --> 00:09:03,105
known mainly for his powers not so much for his insight that was Sariputta so they sat there waiting waiting and finally Moggallana had the gumption to ask you know why don't we start Lord and he said well there's somebody here who shouldn't be here somebody is impure so Moggallana taking his part announced that monk who's impure let him leave the assembly now and nobody moved

74
00:09:05,059 --> 00:09:10,188
So for a second time, let that monk who is impure remove himself from this end.

75
00:09:10,208 --> 00:09:11,029
Nobody, nobody move.

76
00:09:12,292 --> 00:09:23,491
And finally the third time, unlike the Buddha, Moggallana got up from his seat, got hold of this fellow by the arm and looked him out.

77
00:09:25,195 --> 00:09:29,581
An act of force to put right what is wrong.

78
00:09:33,224 --> 00:09:54,674
Apart from those acts, similar occasions, there's another one that comes to mind where the two tribes next to each other, the true ethnic groups I suppose you'd call them now, the Sakians and the Koleans were arguing over river rights and they were getting to a point where they were going to do battle.

79
00:09:54,924 --> 00:10:00,032
And the Buddha turned up and asked them whether the water in the river was equal to the blood in their veins.

80
00:10:00,451 --> 00:10:03,615
And somehow it brought them to their senses and they came to some sort of compromise.

81
00:10:08,282 --> 00:10:16,712
And that's really the sort of major incidents where violence impinges on the Buddha.

82
00:10:18,254 --> 00:10:22,941
In terms of a personal violence of course there's Devadatta who actually tries to kill him.

83
00:10:23,748 --> 00:10:34,562
Coming into old age, Devadatta decided that he was losing it a bit, and it was time for another leader, and he would do very well, thank you very much.

84
00:10:36,404 --> 00:10:39,008
And he thought that the order had gone soft.

85
00:10:40,910 --> 00:10:53,366
Going back to the early days, when he had joined maybe 20, 30 years ago, before monasteries were built, before the order allowed in men and women of not such a high calibre,

86
00:10:54,442 --> 00:11:19,927
it was very strict you mainly lived out in the forest you lived under a tree you only ate one meal a day you only had three robes all these rules began to be softened the Buddha recognized that people couldn't you know not everybody could live at that strictness and and also there was no need for that sort of heavy ascetic practice so many rules were softened for instance

87
00:11:20,649 --> 00:11:41,595
in terms of food now the monks at one point were allowed to go around and take food wherever they wanted but in the early days the monks would have been very ascetic very proper but because there was no rule about when to get food the monks would appear at any time in front of the gate

88
00:11:43,398 --> 00:11:50,488
And instead of the Buddha being hard on that and saying, you know, no, you only have this and that's the end of it.

89
00:11:51,028 --> 00:11:52,529
He came to that middle point, you see.

90
00:11:52,629 --> 00:11:55,553
He said, you can only go out in the morning for your food.

91
00:11:56,315 --> 00:11:58,839
You can have whatever you want, right, but you must finish it by midday.

92
00:11:59,879 --> 00:12:06,428
Now monks complained about that because it would seem that in those times, just as now, the better food is cooked in the afternoon.

93
00:12:08,230 --> 00:12:12,476
So they were getting the morning gruel, really, with a bit of leftovers from yesterday, whatever.

94
00:12:13,654 --> 00:12:43,188
so there was this way of softening things for instance he himself would have spent all his training life out in some sort of forest in some sort of glade or something very shortly after his enlightenment he was offered a monastery by one of his chief supporters name just escapes me now and that meant of course a place and it was near a city

95
00:12:43,472 --> 00:12:48,503
And it meant that as he grew more famous, even kings came to visit him.

96
00:12:49,004 --> 00:12:56,437
So this movement out of the forest towards the city, towards the good life, was something that he had to handle.

97
00:12:57,320 --> 00:13:01,447
So Devadatta saw this all as a great softening, as a dropping of standards.

98
00:13:01,668 --> 00:13:03,311
So he wanted to go back to the original thing.

99
00:13:03,331 --> 00:13:05,294
He even wanted them just to become vegetarians.

100
00:13:07,350 --> 00:13:18,524
So he plotted with one of the kings, well, the king's son, Ajatasattu, who was the son of one of the Buddha's main disciples, Bimbisara.

101
00:13:19,527 --> 00:13:22,210
And he starved his old man to death.

102
00:13:22,910 --> 00:13:28,138
He stuck him in a cell and starved him to death.

103
00:13:28,437 --> 00:13:32,442
And so he was going to rule the kingdom and Devadatta was going to rule the order.

104
00:13:32,984 --> 00:13:36,008
And what Devadatta did was he set this mad elephant onto the Buddha

105
00:13:36,375 --> 00:13:43,212
And the Buddha through his power, you've probably seen the posture of the Buddha, the abhaya posture, the fearless posture.

106
00:13:43,530 --> 00:13:48,235
And he's like this, expressing his fearlessness to the elephant, but also offering loving kindness.

107
00:13:48,475 --> 00:13:52,700
So it's the power of his love that eventually the elephant collapses before him and adores him.

108
00:13:53,821 --> 00:13:57,684
Then there's the occasion where he rolls a big boulder down the hill and it goes over the Buddha's foot.

109
00:13:58,265 --> 00:13:59,206
So he got pretty close.

110
00:14:00,268 --> 00:14:01,048
He got pretty close, right?

111
00:14:01,068 --> 00:14:04,231
He must have, damn, you know, just missed.

112
00:14:04,251 --> 00:14:12,340
The whole story comes to an end when the Buddha sends his two disciples, Sariputra and Moggallana, to go and see Devadatta.

113
00:14:12,893 --> 00:14:18,839
When they arrived, Devadatta, as all these monks that have decided to follow him, he's taken a large chunk of the sangha.

114
00:14:20,240 --> 00:14:26,246
And on the chief disciple's approach, he presumed that they had come to join him.

115
00:14:27,008 --> 00:14:27,769
He was overjoyed.

116
00:14:27,788 --> 00:14:29,410
He says, oh, great, come on in.

117
00:14:30,451 --> 00:14:32,134
And he said, please, give them a talk.

118
00:14:32,453 --> 00:14:33,836
And he himself went for a rest.

119
00:14:34,917 --> 00:14:41,583
While he was resting, Sariputta Magalana argued to the monks that they ought to get back to the Buddha.

120
00:14:42,037 --> 00:15:05,648
so they all upped and left and of course when David Arthur awoke he was very much disturbed according to the myth he was swallowed up into the earth into the worst of hells for eons to come but obviously I think he carried on and in fact the flavour of that reformation comes right through today with the forest tradition which is very ascetic

121
00:15:05,914 --> 00:15:18,120
There's a Danish monk I know, for instance, living up in the north of near Kandy, up in the hills of Sri Lanka, who lives in a three-sided hut in a forest.

122
00:15:18,721 --> 00:15:20,986
That means that snakes, anything can come in and out.

123
00:15:21,307 --> 00:15:23,653
And he just lives on his bed there, you know.

124
00:15:25,708 --> 00:15:40,591
So these are sort of incidents, you might say, in the Buddha's life where he takes personal attack but there's no revenge, there's no response to it except in these sort of kindly ways.

125
00:15:44,756 --> 00:15:51,846
Now, it seems to me that what we're really talking about are two levels of consciousness.

126
00:15:52,928 --> 00:15:53,590
And

127
00:15:54,903 --> 00:16:06,822
If what we understand by a level of consciousness is a way of understanding the world, a way of seeing the world, then I think we can distinguish between these two approaches, pacifism and the just war.

128
00:16:08,605 --> 00:16:14,813
To give you a very sharp example of a shift in consciousness is the age between six and eight.

129
00:16:15,816 --> 00:16:20,302
So for a six-year-old, Father Christmas coming down the chimney is no problem.

130
00:16:20,705 --> 00:16:22,687
For an eight-year-old, it's a big problem.

131
00:16:23,708 --> 00:16:37,705
And what's happened is, of course, is that the child comes to a reality testing of its fantasies, of its energetic life, begins to understand that what it imagines is not always true.

132
00:16:38,046 --> 00:16:40,808
So there's a movement towards reality.

133
00:16:41,649 --> 00:16:46,655
Secondly, of course, this whole business of morality comes in with the attendant guilt and all that.

134
00:16:47,015 --> 00:16:49,158
It's not that a young child doesn't feel that.

135
00:16:49,527 --> 00:17:16,615
it was a rather interesting occasion with a friend's child who was about four and for some reason he had taken something which he shouldn't have taken and it had been on his mind and he actually became ill and when he finally got it out and told his parents that he'd taken this thing the illness disappeared so

136
00:17:17,589 --> 00:17:47,226
I think that's a very premature feeling of guilt personally you know I don't see three-year-olds too worried about taking things they don't know so normally we associate that with seven and of course in our culture that's mythologized in the Garden of Eden isn't it where Adam and Eve approach the tree of good and evil the knowledge of good and evil and although in our tradition Eve of course is the evil thing and the destroyer of heaven of mankind

137
00:17:47,644 --> 00:18:14,866
from a point of view of the movement of consciousness Eve is given the primary task of shifting it so she's actually lifted human consciousness out of its six, five-year-old state from a Buddhist point of view she's a heroine, not a devil so if we have that sort of thing in mind then you can see there's a shift

138
00:18:15,843 --> 00:18:36,720
from a person who believes in a self to a person who doesn't have a self now if I have a self I have these attitudes I am greedy I'm averse to anything which poses a problem to me and I'll run from anything which is too great

139
00:18:38,606 --> 00:18:50,909
So in terms of greediness, for instance, should we say, take a fairly recent example, Saddam's little sojourning into Kuwait.

140
00:18:52,131 --> 00:18:58,201
That's obviously him trying to extend this idea of the pan-Arabic nation.

141
00:18:58,721 --> 00:19:00,103
And it's a grandism, isn't it?

142
00:19:00,324 --> 00:19:01,345
Because he's going to be the head of it.

143
00:19:01,444 --> 00:19:09,032
I mean, it's not as though he goes there and gives the Kuwaiti prince the charge of all Arab nations.

144
00:19:09,093 --> 00:19:10,134
He's going to be there.

145
00:19:10,153 --> 00:19:13,096
So that's obviously a ward of aggression, a ward of aggrandizement.

146
00:19:15,259 --> 00:19:20,263
That, I think, is fairly easy to show that that is just not justifiable.

147
00:19:20,865 --> 00:19:22,346
That's not a problem for the self.

148
00:19:23,207 --> 00:19:25,789
However, from the Kuwaiti's point of view, they're being attacked.

149
00:19:26,691 --> 00:19:27,852
You see, they're being attacked.

150
00:19:28,252 --> 00:19:31,036
Now the self must protect itself.

151
00:19:32,317 --> 00:19:47,311
So there is long argument in both our own law and in laws of any religion and state whereby you can defend yourself because you're defending your life and you have to defend your life because you've got a self to defend.

152
00:19:49,354 --> 00:19:52,978
So now the problem is how are you going to defend yourself?

153
00:19:53,650 --> 00:20:03,644
If you defend yourself with violence, then that will lead to all sorts of consequences of revenge and all that sort of stuff, isn't it?

154
00:20:06,008 --> 00:20:11,596
And you find that wars continue because of this vengefulness, because of this vengefulness.

155
00:20:14,141 --> 00:20:23,134
Even in our own recent history, you see, after the First World War, there was huge, enormous reparations demanded of Germany.

156
00:20:23,636 --> 00:20:26,442
which just threw them into abject poverty.

157
00:20:27,163 --> 00:20:32,873
And it was out of that that somebody like Hitler could arise, and then you've got another war on your hand.

158
00:20:32,893 --> 00:20:39,163
After the Second World War, happily, people understood, and nothing was demanded.

159
00:20:39,244 --> 00:20:47,940
In fact, the Marshall Plan rebuilt Germany, and a whole new idea of Europe came in after those two world wars.

160
00:20:49,269 --> 00:20:58,964
So we can see this ability to defend ourselves, for a self to defend itself, without the violence, without the sense of revenge.

161
00:20:59,546 --> 00:21:05,095
So here we have now this business of America in Afghanistan.

162
00:21:05,115 --> 00:21:10,482
It's difficult to think that there isn't a sense of revenge in Bush and those soldiers.

163
00:21:10,522 --> 00:21:16,813
There probably is, but luckily it's been very much contained by the fact that they have to keep

164
00:21:17,147 --> 00:21:33,654
good friends with Muslim neighbors they can't just go in there and belt everybody up otherwise no doubt in the heat of after that catastrophe they probably would have done it they probably just you know I mean who's going to stop them you know who has the power to stop them to do it simple as that you know

165
00:21:34,106 --> 00:21:42,340
So what stopped them, obviously, was the Muslim nations who didn't want an all out destruction of Afghanistan.

166
00:21:42,761 --> 00:21:49,534
And, of course, the balancing act of especially Europeans who also don't want that sort of catastrophe, you know.

167
00:21:51,589 --> 00:22:07,169
So, in a sense, the war in Afghanistan was described as a just war in terms of, you know, there you have this man, this, what's his name, Bin Laden, who really has gone beyond the pale.

168
00:22:07,750 --> 00:22:13,016
See, what do you do with somebody who says that the ends justify the means?

169
00:22:14,778 --> 00:22:16,681
See, it's totally amoral.

170
00:22:16,881 --> 00:22:20,365
It's not immoral, there's just no morality involved.

171
00:22:20,951 --> 00:22:29,679
anything works so long as I get to the ends I want that was beautifully portrayed in that film I can't remember who the director was, Apocalypse Now?

172
00:22:30,720 --> 00:22:50,217
where the American general the American army have decided to get rid of this American general and the reason is because they think he's gone mad but what he wants to do is treat the Viet Cong like the Viet Cong are treating the Americans no holes barred and he wants to drop the bomb and win the war

173
00:22:51,444 --> 00:23:21,434
so you come against this business of the ends justify the means and when you're up against an enemy such as a sworn enemy such as bin Laden then really what option have you got apart from to use force from a self point of view from this self point of view if we now take the argument down a slot back into our ordinary civil life

174
00:23:23,525 --> 00:23:26,347
We expect the police to use force.

175
00:23:26,367 --> 00:23:29,311
We don't expect them to use violence.

176
00:23:29,551 --> 00:23:39,064
Whenever the police are involved in a violent situation, let's call it a violent situation where they're being attacked and all that, we expect them to be restrained.

177
00:23:39,324 --> 00:23:42,106
We don't expect policemen to take their revenge on others.

178
00:23:42,847 --> 00:23:48,654
That's why I think it was probably very shocking that these Italian police went and shot these people.

179
00:23:48,938 --> 00:23:49,719
They shot him.

180
00:23:50,240 --> 00:23:51,582
I mean, they weren't even armed.

181
00:23:52,021 --> 00:23:53,585
It was absolutely outrageous.

182
00:23:54,425 --> 00:23:55,627
I don't know what's happening about that.

183
00:23:55,647 --> 00:23:59,553
There's supposed to be some sort of investigation about it.

184
00:23:59,854 --> 00:24:06,103
But that, from I think most people's point of view, is just completely over the top.

185
00:24:06,808 --> 00:24:21,734
So, you know, we always have this problem, like there was a case, I think, maybe in Liverpool or something, where this man with a great machete or something was going around and he was about down the street or something, and the police shot him, you see.

186
00:24:22,096 --> 00:24:24,199
So now the question is, did they have to shoot him?

187
00:24:24,380 --> 00:24:27,464
You know, why didn't they shoot him in the leg, for instance, or why did they kill him?

188
00:24:27,905 --> 00:24:28,547
You see what I mean?

189
00:24:29,219 --> 00:24:57,166
so these questions are always going to come up as to the edge between justifiable force to put right what is wrong and force which shifts into violence with something added you know like he's a useless anyway we'll get rid of him shoot him in the head you don't know what what the policeman's thinking when he does it is it in our own family in our own family situation right up until i think in britain anyway right up until

190
00:24:57,518 --> 00:25:00,061
the early 60s, the family was sacrosanct.

191
00:25:00,082 --> 00:25:00,863
You couldn't go into it.

192
00:25:01,785 --> 00:25:10,499
If the wife was being beaten up, if the kids were being maltreated, and if occasionally the husband was being beaten up, you couldn't go in.

193
00:25:10,519 --> 00:25:11,881
It was a locked unit.

194
00:25:12,582 --> 00:25:16,167
It had nothing to do with, you know, even...

195
00:25:16,621 --> 00:25:17,902
I had an incident like that.

196
00:25:18,123 --> 00:25:20,565
I got off the bus where I was living in Birmingham.

197
00:25:20,585 --> 00:25:25,750
And right across the road, I could see this woman being kicked by this man, you know, in the head.

198
00:25:25,790 --> 00:25:26,592
I saw it.

199
00:25:26,612 --> 00:25:30,496
And so I went over, you know, and, you know, I sort of stood in between them.

200
00:25:30,516 --> 00:25:31,396
He was going to have another go.

201
00:25:31,477 --> 00:25:32,959
So I sort of stood in between them.

202
00:25:32,999 --> 00:25:36,281
And so I just said to him, I think you've done a lot of damage here, you know.

203
00:25:36,301 --> 00:25:37,542
And it sort of came to his senses.

204
00:25:38,104 --> 00:25:38,664
And off he went.

205
00:25:39,144 --> 00:25:40,386
As it turned out, it was a husband.

206
00:25:41,407 --> 00:25:41,768
It's okay.

207
00:25:41,748 --> 00:25:43,411
In the middle of the street there.

208
00:25:43,431 --> 00:25:47,237
So I helped this woman up and I said, look, what do you want to do?

209
00:25:47,517 --> 00:25:48,097
How bad are you?

210
00:25:48,538 --> 00:25:49,881
And she didn't seem to be that bad.

211
00:25:49,921 --> 00:25:57,272
I mean, she'd been sort of kicked, but it didn't seem as though she was necessary to hospitalise her, at least that's what I thought.

212
00:25:57,673 --> 00:25:58,855
So I said, what do you want to do?

213
00:25:59,016 --> 00:26:02,862
And it occurred to me that perhaps this ought to be reported to the police.

214
00:26:03,262 --> 00:26:11,758
So we walked up onto the main road and I must have looked as I was trying to help her, you know, walk, because I think she was a bit unsteady.

215
00:26:11,999 --> 00:26:16,145
And a car stopped very kindly and took us a lift to a local police station.

216
00:26:16,165 --> 00:26:19,250
Well, we got off and I was sort of amazed, really.

217
00:26:19,592 --> 00:26:21,255
I went in there and I said...

218
00:26:21,961 --> 00:26:25,125
She'd like to report, you know, grievous bodily harm.

219
00:26:25,166 --> 00:26:30,635
She's just been really battered, kicked to the ground and all sorts by her husband and we want to, you know.

220
00:26:31,076 --> 00:26:33,781
And the policeman basically sort of looked blank at us.

221
00:26:34,682 --> 00:26:36,365
They're like, what can I do, you know?

222
00:26:36,747 --> 00:26:41,173
And I suddenly realised, yeah, well, you know, like there was no procedure for it.

223
00:26:41,193 --> 00:26:46,163
There was no, there didn't seem to be any particular interest in it at all, you see.

224
00:26:46,565 --> 00:26:49,288
However, the law is changed.

225
00:26:49,809 --> 00:27:09,061
As we know, even if a neighbour, and some of them use it for evil reasons, nefarious reasons, if a neighbour reports that they heard a child scream in the next house, you've got the social services, the police, you've got everybody darting in there to see if you can sort it out.

226
00:27:09,785 --> 00:27:20,840
so this suggests that society at base understands that where there's violence one can use force to put an end to it

227
00:27:21,884 --> 00:27:45,933
you know justifiable force we're coming now to an international situation where the world community feels that in a given violent situation you can go in there and use force the Balkans is an obvious place Macedonia recently where there was more ethnic trouble the EU and you know got involved

228
00:27:46,858 --> 00:28:01,442
and very recently and it's only you know is actual war criminals being brought before justice and things like that so you can see that the idea of using force to put an end to an evil

229
00:28:01,792 --> 00:28:29,505
is justifiable now both at an ordinary national level and international level you see now that's jihad that's what jihad is supposed to be it's a just war that's what Saint Thomas Aquinas would have argued for the problem is that there's no such argument in Buddhism no such argument in Buddhism there's no argument in Buddhism to do something towards gratuitous violence

230
00:28:30,380 --> 00:28:55,948
you see and this meant for instance when the Turkish armies came into India the Muslim Turkish armies and they saw this statue of a Buddha and all that which was horrific to them they simply wiped out monasteries and monks they killed them all now the Hindus were also under that sort of attack they were also persecuted but they had a philosophy to help them fight back

231
00:28:56,519 --> 00:29:23,843
to help them you know use well I presume sometimes it was violent force but definitely they had a philosophy and it's in the Bhagavad Gita and it's in the story of Arjuna who has to fight his own family the evil ones and Krishna is by his side and Arjuna says he can't do it he can't kill his own people and Krishna's argument is that he has a duty for the good

232
00:29:25,492 --> 00:29:28,857
Now, whether his own people or not, his duty is to put right what is wrong.

233
00:29:29,578 --> 00:29:33,144
And Arjuna goes on, of course, to defeat these enemies.

234
00:29:34,326 --> 00:29:39,074
And therein is established, at least in a mythological sense, the idea of a just war.

235
00:29:48,127 --> 00:29:51,653
So, from the point of view of the self...

236
00:29:52,830 --> 00:30:04,287
understanding that the vast majority, the vast, vast majority of human beings at this present time in our development believe very strongly in a self.

237
00:30:04,307 --> 00:30:12,357
There is justifiable moral law to say that they can defend their lives, they can defend their own people, they can defend their country.

238
00:30:13,891 --> 00:30:15,452
We would all agree with that.

239
00:30:15,472 --> 00:30:26,750
I don't think it would be hard for Buddhism even to argue against that, even though as far as I know, there's no incident of such a thing in the discourses.

240
00:30:28,173 --> 00:30:35,965
One of the things about the discourses is that, of course, they tend to be centered very much on the Dharma, and you get very little about the society around.

241
00:30:35,986 --> 00:30:38,650
You don't get much sort of history like this.

242
00:30:41,701 --> 00:31:09,548
now if there's no self to defend we're moving into a very strange area for us so we have this saying by the Buddha I think it's in the Dhammapada where he said should someone approach you with a sword and cut you up to pieces if hatred arises in your heart towards that person you are no disciple of mine that's pretty tough isn't it

243
00:31:09,932 --> 00:31:32,582
so what's the what is the psychology of pacifism true pacifism right not armchair pacifism not pacifists who wouldn't want to go to war they won't kill anybody but somehow there's um maybe even though it's put in this wonderful justifiable language there's a hint of cowardice underneath

244
00:31:33,642 --> 00:31:37,086
I met a very interesting man when I was out in the East.

245
00:31:37,226 --> 00:31:43,733
He was an American who had fled, well, he'd gone into Canada, escaping the draft from Vietnam.

246
00:31:44,474 --> 00:31:47,959
And, of course, he had very rational reasons for doing so, as many of them did.

247
00:31:48,579 --> 00:31:57,410
But there was in him this niggling doubt as to whether, in fact, he'd not done it because he basically didn't want to fight, he was afraid.

248
00:31:57,891 --> 00:31:59,952
You know, you get killed, don't you, in war?

249
00:32:01,807 --> 00:32:17,528
And what he did to, funnily enough, what he did to prove that it wasn't a case of lack of courage was he walked through the Cambodian jungle from one end to the other, this big jungle for about two or three weeks.

250
00:32:17,568 --> 00:32:20,633
I can't remember now, but it was something that nobody in their right mind would do.

251
00:32:22,415 --> 00:32:23,336
And he just went like that.

252
00:32:23,416 --> 00:32:25,619
He told me he went in a straight line, didn't shift.

253
00:32:26,173 --> 00:32:30,621
He just kept going and going and going and going, meeting with all sorts of things.

254
00:32:31,422 --> 00:32:43,760
And after that, he felt he'd exercised out of himself this idea that he'd not joined the war because of cowardice.

255
00:32:44,128 --> 00:33:13,832
that he had actually done it in good faith he'd done it in good faith maybe there was cowardice there but he'd done it in good faith and that if he had been forced to go then he would have gone so the pacifist stand you see what's that based on you see so we have to project as it were onto human beings as a society the way we treat ourselves

256
00:33:14,757 --> 00:33:41,170
when anger arises within us we bear it and we know it'll die out now can we now project that psychology on all human beings when they come to us with anger can we take it and be a funnel for that anger to be drawn out of the system now one of the great archetypes

257
00:33:41,960 --> 00:33:59,361
in human history of that of course is Jesus Christ because that's what he does he is the sacrificial victim he's the one who having stated the truth having been a truth which the authorities saw as subversion

258
00:34:00,049 --> 00:34:29,094
and therefore it became a political problem decided to get rid of him in a very unjust trial and he says nothing he doesn't fight it he just takes that violence into him and in so doing manifests a way of being with anger undoing anger that sort of philosophy runs through people like Gandhi

259
00:34:29,411 --> 00:34:46,695
civil disobedience yes but being able to take the blows if you remember in the film the soldiers kept whopping on so he must have been an enormously charismatic person to get people to do that when you think about it

260
00:34:46,675 --> 00:35:11,467
I mean can you imagine the Americans have taken the blow of the Twin Towers you know and appealed to the world community to should we say undermine that evil without them using force you know to take to take the actual blow as it were people like Aung San Suu Kyi you see she

261
00:35:12,898 --> 00:35:21,041
The worst part of the troubles, the real part where the government were just shooting, even children in the street, they were just shooting them here and there.

262
00:35:22,364 --> 00:35:28,139
She stood right in front of the army, right in front of the guns and said, if you want to shoot me, shoot me, you see, just took them on.

263
00:35:30,112 --> 00:35:35,016
Of course, what helps these people is their charisma, their aura, their reputation.

264
00:35:35,458 --> 00:35:39,461
You know, she was the daughter of the first leader of Burma after independence.

265
00:35:40,302 --> 00:35:41,503
So she has that aura, you see.

266
00:35:41,563 --> 00:35:44,166
Gandhi has the aura, you see.

267
00:35:44,186 --> 00:35:49,893
If an ordinary person had done it, you see, you'd get shot.

268
00:35:49,914 --> 00:35:52,817
Although we have that incident, don't we, in China, Tiananmen Square.

269
00:35:53,056 --> 00:35:58,583
But before Tiananmen Square, when the tanks came in and that man stood in front of a tank and they just all stopped,

270
00:35:59,068 --> 00:36:00,791
And he offered, I think he offered him a flower, didn't he?

271
00:36:01,510 --> 00:36:05,956
Sort of a later day version of the flower power.

272
00:36:08,077 --> 00:36:09,458
But eventually, of course, that didn't work either.

273
00:36:10,880 --> 00:36:28,097
So, Martin Luther King, see, finding a way through all that racism and stuff in a peaceful way, but in the end, he himself takes the blow, you see, but he stands now as a martyr, he stands as a figure, an archetype of how

274
00:36:28,465 --> 00:36:54,574
these relations can be brought to a more peaceful end you see Nelson Mandela and I think that South Africa has given to the world a wonderful example of a non-violent solution through these what do they call them reconciliation counts they weren't trials sorry

275
00:36:54,958 --> 00:36:57,302
were they?

276
00:36:58,623 --> 00:37:13,985
where people were allowed just to give the truth and then if they just spoke the truth so that people knew because a line had been drawn in history there was no need for revenge there was no need to do you know what I mean?

277
00:37:14,005 --> 00:37:22,637
and that of course is a wonderful thing if you can do that so we have this

278
00:37:22,887 --> 00:37:50,952
higher consciousness which doesn't see human being sorry doesn't see cells it doesn't see human beings what it sees is forces it sees violent force turbulent force just as we see in ourselves and it sees loving force it's not caught up in I am me I have to defend me you are you you see it's just this interrelationship and out of compassion one as it were offers oneself

279
00:37:51,338 --> 00:37:54,161
the sacrifice to absorb that violence.

280
00:37:55,003 --> 00:37:56,804
That's the pacifist.

281
00:37:56,824 --> 00:38:03,172
So how would a pacifist have done something about Afghanistan?

282
00:38:04,974 --> 00:38:20,215
It seems to me that one thing pacifists could have done, really could have done, through the internet, through telephone calls, would have been, for all of them, as many as possible, I don't know, a million, two million, with all these wonderful Nobel Prize winners for peace.

283
00:38:20,751 --> 00:38:43,485
to have congregated on the borders of Afghanistan and walked in completely unarmed now they may very well have been shot a lot of them might have died but eventually if so many of them flooded the country with argument slowly they would have got the sympathy of people

284
00:38:44,663 --> 00:38:55,954
And eventually, they might have brought about a revolution, not just simply in terms of government, but in terms of heart, in terms of what are these Afghanis doing to each other?

285
00:38:56,195 --> 00:39:00,960
I mean, we blame these Taliban people, but they've been slaughtering each other for years now.

286
00:39:04,003 --> 00:39:04,364
Maybe.

287
00:39:04,523 --> 00:39:05,164
I don't know.

288
00:39:05,184 --> 00:39:07,067
It's just one idea.

289
00:39:07,086 --> 00:39:10,309
There's no infrastructure whatsoever.

290
00:39:10,329 --> 00:39:12,052
No.

291
00:39:12,072 --> 00:39:13,253
For Afghanistan.

292
00:39:13,925 --> 00:39:16,788
Yes, how do you get all these people in there?

293
00:39:16,807 --> 00:39:18,809
There's not even anything for the people who live there.

294
00:39:19,449 --> 00:39:27,657
Well, that's it, you see, but you'd work out ... You'd work away, if you really thought that might be a solution, you know.

295
00:39:32,081 --> 00:39:42,092
It's just an idea, I mean, I don't know, I've not thought of it in terms of logistics or anything, but definitely, if you want to affect a situation,

296
00:39:42,376 --> 00:39:45,820
which is violent, then you've got to go in with peaceful motives.

297
00:39:46,181 --> 00:39:50,387
Like in Northern Ireland, she was young then, Devlin, wasn't it?

298
00:39:50,507 --> 00:39:51,268
Bernadette Devlin.

299
00:39:53,012 --> 00:39:54,094
Frontline stuff, you know.

300
00:39:56,356 --> 00:40:03,166
So if we understand that, I think that we can take certain positions, so we say.

301
00:40:03,887 --> 00:40:06,391
I think we can say that from a Buddhist point of view,

302
00:40:06,742 --> 00:40:18,463
a pacifist approach definitely is the more skillful and will bring much longer lasting results to a society.

303
00:40:21,188 --> 00:40:31,367
I think using force, so long as the force is measured and to the point and so long as afterwards reparations are made,

304
00:40:31,853 --> 00:40:37,539
as they're trying to do now with Afghanistan, I think that also may have very much a similar outcome.

305
00:40:38,661 --> 00:40:41,304
And I think that's justifiable, personally.

306
00:40:41,324 --> 00:40:48,914
I think that a Buddhist need not feel guilty for supporting force in a given situation, so long as those conditions are there.

307
00:40:50,114 --> 00:40:55,161
Because it's not gone with violence, it's not gone with revenge, it's just gone to put something right which is wrong.

308
00:40:55,697 --> 00:41:05,914
And we have again an example even in Christ's own life where he turns the tables in the temple and gets the moneylenders to leave.

309
00:41:06,355 --> 00:41:12,025
Now, it's unfortunate that a lot of Christians actually see that as anger and they talk about justifiable anger.

310
00:41:12,726 --> 00:41:22,802
And that sort of amazes me because it's not making a distinction between anger, aggression and assertion.

311
00:41:22,985 --> 00:41:26,911
You know, sometimes you've got to say, well, that's wrong, and out you go.

312
00:41:26,951 --> 00:41:28,713
See?

313
00:41:29,014 --> 00:41:33,840
I can imagine him doing that without any anger, just with a forceful voice, you know, headmasterish.

314
00:41:34,822 --> 00:41:35,682
Leave this room immediately.

315
00:41:36,804 --> 00:41:37,525
All that sort of stuff.

316
00:41:39,108 --> 00:41:39,489
See?

317
00:41:39,688 --> 00:41:42,132
I don't see why that had to have aggression in it at all.

318
00:41:42,572 --> 00:41:45,978
But of course, the moneylenders would have seen it as aggression.

319
00:41:45,998 --> 00:41:46,217
See?

320
00:41:46,659 --> 00:41:48,440
And the authorities would have seen it as aggression.

321
00:41:49,882 --> 00:41:52,367
Yes, are you saying that, I think you said that

322
00:41:52,768 --> 00:41:59,786
in terms of society views itself as a collection of selves, then there is an argument for a just war.

323
00:42:00,186 --> 00:42:09,208
But are you saying that if you take the higher consciousness viewpoint that there is no self, then you're saying there isn't a just war on it?

324
00:42:09,661 --> 00:42:14,266
Well, I think that you can then argue for a pacifist approach.

325
00:42:14,947 --> 00:42:17,969
Or rather, you can see how pacifism works.

326
00:42:18,891 --> 00:42:23,996
But even at that level, I would argue that force can be used.

327
00:42:25,117 --> 00:42:32,485
To give you one final example, the Dalai Lama, you see, now this is what I've heard, I don't actually know whether he said this or not, right?

328
00:42:33,025 --> 00:42:36,528
But he was asked in those heady days when we thought we were going to blow each other to bits,

329
00:42:36,509 --> 00:42:40,592
would he kill the person who was about to press the button?

330
00:42:41,173 --> 00:43:04,456
and he said he would for the benefit of all beings it's a utilitarian argument it's for the benefit of the many but he said he would take the karma he would take the consequences of that killing now my argument would be if he did it out of compassion if that was his main intention he did it out of compassion where would the bad karma be?

331
00:43:10,411 --> 00:43:14,965
I shall leave you with that conundrum.

332
00:43:14,985 --> 00:43:19,016
I hope it's been of some benefit to sort one or two problems out.

333
00:43:21,826 --> 00:43:22,226
Very good.

